{
  "id": "exhaust-aggregation",
  "name": "Aggregation paradox",
  "desc": "Aggregation creates monopoly even when regulation intended openness, because platform-scale combination of data from many sources creates market power that individual data access rights cannot counteract.",
  "picks": {
    "Capability Class": {
      "value": "Frontier",
      "memo": "Aggregation paradox operates at frontier capability where scale-driven processing creates aggregate intelligence that smaller systems cannot produce.",
      "detail": "Frontier capability enables the sophisticated aggregation that creates market power through superior analytical combination of diverse inputs. The scale of processing required to aggregate effectively demands frontier-level compute and model capability. Frontier systems can detect patterns across aggregated datasets that smaller models miss entirely. The capability level determines whether aggregation creates genuine market power or merely collects data."
    },
    "Domain Breadth": {
      "value": "General",
      "memo": "General domain breadth enables the aggregation paradox because cross-domain data combination creates insights unavailable from any single domain or source.",
      "detail": "General breadth means the aggregator combines data across every domain, creating comprehensive intelligence that domain-specific actors cannot match. Cross-domain aggregation is where the paradox emerges: mandated openness in each domain enables monopoly through combination. The general breadth creates the comprehensive view that makes the aggregated product more valuable than any individual contribution. Domain breadth determines the scope and severity of the aggregation-driven monopoly."
    },
    "Capability Trajectory": {
      "value": "Rapid",
      "memo": "Rapid capability trajectory strengthens the aggregation paradox because improving analytical capability continuously extracts more value from the same aggregated datasets.",
      "detail": "Rapid trajectory means each model improvement discovers new aggregation value from existing datasets without requiring new data sources. The acceleration compounds aggregation advantage because better models produce better aggregate intelligence from unchanged inputs. Rapid improvement widens the gap between the aggregator's analytical capability and individual data contributors. The trajectory determines how quickly aggregation power concentrates and how fast competitive positions become unassailable."
    },
    "Research Automation": {
      "value": "AI-assisted",
      "memo": "AI-assisted research enables the aggregator to discover new combination patterns and cross-source insights that human analysis alone could not identify.",
      "detail": "AI-assisted research means models help identify aggregation opportunities and cross-source combination strategies that create maximum value. Human strategists guide the aggregation direction while AI discovers specific patterns and value extraction methods. The combination enables aggregation at sophistication and scale that neither humans nor machines alone could achieve. AI assistance in aggregation compounds the market power that the paradox describes."
    },
    "Unhobbling": {
      "value": "Workflow agent",
      "memo": "Workflow-agent unhobbling enables automated aggregation pipelines that continuously collect, combine, and distribute aggregate intelligence across multiple data sources.",
      "detail": "Workflow agent means the system coordinates multi-step aggregation processes across diverse data sources and analytical tasks. The agent manages the complete aggregation workflow from data collection through combination to product distribution. Workflow-level automation enables the scale of aggregation that creates market power. The unhobbling level determines the operational capability and throughput of the aggregation engine."
    },
    "Replication Scale": {
      "value": "Many copies",
      "memo": "Many copies of aggregation systems operate in parallel across different data domains and geographies, building comprehensive coverage that creates market dominance.",
      "detail": "Many copies means aggregation systems run simultaneously across different data domains, markets, and geographic regions. This parallel operation enables comprehensive data coverage that individual or regional actors cannot match. The replication scale is what transforms aggregation from useful tool into market-dominant platform. Many-copy aggregation is the mechanism through which the paradox of regulated openness creating monopoly emerges."
    },
    "Operating Speed": {
      "value": "Faster-than-human",
      "memo": "Faster-than-human aggregation speed means the platform processes, combines, and distributes aggregate intelligence before individual data producers can respond.",
      "detail": "Faster-than-human speed means the aggregator processes and combines data faster than individual contributors can monitor or counteract. By the time data producers recognise the aggregation dynamic, the platform has already established market dominance. Speed asymmetry between aggregation and producer response is a key mechanism of market power accumulation. The speed advantage means the aggregation paradox compounds before any regulatory or competitive response can form."
    },
    "Physical World Extension": {
      "value": "Cognitive-only",
      "memo": "The aggregation paradox operates in the cognitive domain where data combination and analytical processing create the market power that physical assets cannot match.",
      "detail": "Cognitive-only means the monopoly power comes from information aggregation and analysis rather than physical asset control. The paradox is specifically about how information combination creates market power that physical-world competition cannot erode. Cognitive-only focus demonstrates that the aggregation paradox is an information economics phenomenon. The market power is created through data processing, not through physical infrastructure dominance."
    },
    "Role": {
      "value": "Workflow owner",
      "memo": "The aggregation platform functions as a workflow owner that controls the complete data collection, combination, analysis, and distribution pipeline creating market power.",
      "detail": "Workflow owner role means the aggregator controls the entire aggregation process from data collection through combination to product distribution. The platform does not merely assist with aggregation but owns and operates the complete analytical workflow. Workflow ownership is what creates the market power because the aggregator controls access to the combined intelligence. The role determines whether aggregation serves individual users or creates platform-dominant market positions."
    },
    "Actuation": {
      "value": "Digital action",
      "memo": "Aggregation operates through digital action channels where platform-scale data combination and distribution creates market dominance through information processing.",
      "detail": "Digital action means the aggregator creates market power through computational combination and distribution of information. The actuation is entirely through data processing and analytical product distribution channels. Digital aggregation at platform scale creates market dominance that physical distribution networks could not achieve. The actuation channel is where the aggregation paradox manifests as real economic market power."
    },
    "Autonomy": {
      "value": "Exception-supervised",
      "memo": "Aggregation systems operate with exception supervision where automated collection and combination runs continuously with human oversight for quality and compliance anomalies.",
      "detail": "Exception-supervised autonomy means aggregation pipelines operate continuously with human analysts reviewing flagged quality and compliance issues. The automation enables the scale and speed of aggregation that creates market dominance. Exception supervision balances operational throughput with compliance and quality governance. The autonomy level enables sustained platform-scale aggregation without requiring human approval for each data combination."
    },
    "Delegated Authority": {
      "value": "Operational mandate",
      "memo": "Aggregation platforms receive operational mandates through regulatory open-access requirements that grant broad authority to collect and combine data from mandated sources.",
      "detail": "Operational mandate means the aggregator operates under regulatory frameworks that mandate data access for specified purposes. The mandate provides legitimate authority for data collection that individual negotiations could not achieve. Regulatory mandates intended to promote competition instead provide the aggregation authority that creates monopoly. Operational mandate through regulation is the mechanism that creates the paradox of openness enabling concentration."
    },
    "Tool Access": {
      "value": "Broad toolchain",
      "memo": "Aggregation platforms access broad toolchains spanning data collection APIs, analytical processing engines, distribution systems, and cross-source combination capabilities.",
      "detail": "Broad toolchain means the aggregator accesses diverse data sources, analytical tools, and distribution channels across the entire data ecosystem. The breadth of access enables the comprehensive aggregation that creates market dominance. Each additional tool and data source strengthens the platform's aggregate intelligence and market position. Broad toolchain access is the operational infrastructure of the aggregation paradox."
    },
    "Response / Intervention Capability": {
      "value": "Defined escalation",
      "memo": "Aggregation platforms have defined escalation procedures for handling data quality issues, source disputes, and compliance challenges through structured governance processes.",
      "detail": "Defined escalation means clear procedures exist for handling data quality problems, source access disputes, and regulatory compliance questions. The escalation paths assign responsibility and timeline for resolution through institutional governance processes. Defined escalation demonstrates that aggregation operates within institutional governance even when creating market power. The escalation framework manages the operational challenges of platform-scale data aggregation."
    },
    "Command Actor": {
      "value": "Enterprise",
      "memo": "Enterprise command means the aggregation platform's corporate leadership determines aggregation scope, market strategy, and how regulatory openness is commercially exploited.",
      "detail": "Enterprise command means corporate strategy drives decisions about what data to aggregate, how to combine it, and how to distribute the result. The enterprise decides which mandated access rights to exploit and how aggressively to pursue aggregation-driven market power. Enterprise command determines whether aggregation serves broad market benefit or narrow platform enrichment. Corporate strategy over aggregation is what converts regulatory openness into commercial monopoly."
    },
    "Decision Tempo": {
      "value": "Product cycle",
