    },
    "Permission": {
      "value": "Broad",
      "memo": "Aggregation platforms operate under broad permission granted by open-access regulations that mandate data availability without anticipating aggregation-driven monopoly consequences.",
      "detail": "Broad permission means regulatory frameworks grant extensive data access rights intended to promote competition and market openness. The broad permission was designed to enable individual access but inadvertently enables platform-scale aggregation. The permission is legally sound because the regulations mandated exactly this kind of open access. Broad permission through regulation is the legal foundation that makes the aggregation paradox possible."
    },
    "Regulatory Posture": {
      "value": "Mandated open",
      "memo": "Aggregation exploits mandated-open regulatory posture where forced data sharing creates the input availability that enables platform-scale monopolistic combination.",
      "detail": "Mandated open regulation means data availability is legally required to promote competition, access, and market function. The mandated openness provides the aggregator with guaranteed access to data from multiple sources without negotiation friction. The paradox emerges because mandated openness enables aggregation that concentrates rather than distributes market power. Mandated-open regulation creating monopoly through aggregation is the regulatory failure the stance highlights."
    },
    "Data Availability": {
      "value": "Open/available",
      "memo": "Data availability is open because regulation mandates it, creating the paradoxical condition where mandated openness enables aggregation-driven market concentration.",
      "detail": "Open/available data means anyone can access the data, including platform-scale aggregators. The openness was intended to enable individual competition but platform-scale players can combine open data far more effectively than individual actors. Open availability is the necessary precondition for the aggregation paradox because it eliminates access barriers. The openness that was meant to prevent monopoly through data hoarding instead enables monopoly through data combination."
    },
    "Provenance": {
      "value": "Mixed/declared",
      "memo": "Aggregated data has mixed provenance combining inputs from diverse mandated, licensed, and public sources into products whose origins are difficult to untangle.",
      "detail": "Mixed/declared provenance means the aggregated product combines data from many sources with varying levels of attribution and origin documentation. The mixed character makes it difficult for individual data producers to trace their contribution to aggregate products. Declared provenance at the source level does not translate to verifiable provenance at the aggregate product level. Mixed provenance in aggregate products obscures the individual contributions that regulation intended to empower."
    },
